    "description": "# Khazna\n\n## What is the problem Khazna is trying to solve?\n\nKhazna aims to provide a secure way to provide sensitive data (passwords, AWS credentials, ... ) to automated scripts running in an unattended manner (scheduled using cron, or invoked remotely , ... ) so that if the user account from which the automated script is being run gets compromised, the attacker can't retrieve the sensitive data.\n\n## How Khazna tries to solve this problem?\n\nKhazna is a parameter store that uses context-based authentication to allow or deny access to sensitive data. This means that instead of just authenticating \"WHO\" is requesting the parameter (the user account running the automated script), it authenticates \"WHAT\" the parameter is going to be used for and \"HOW\" it is being run.\n\nThis means that you can create rules for the below use cases and many more:\n\n1. Only pass the parameter to a certain script (verified by the hash).\n2. Only pass the parameter if the script is invoked from an SSH session open from a certain IP.\n3. Only pass the parameter if the script is invoked from cron.\n4. Only pass the parameter if the script is invoked from a non-interactive shell.\n\n## URL\n\nhttps://github.com/mohamed-osama-aboelkheir/Khazna",
